
<section>
<title>Substitution</title>
<p>
{\tmstrong{Objective: Solve systems of equations using substitution.}}\pp
</p>
  
<p>
Solving a system of equations by graphing has several limitations. First, it requires
the graph to be perfectly drawn, if the lines are not straight we may arrive
at the wrong answer. Second, graphing is not a great method to use if the
answer is really large, over 100 for example, or a decimal, since
a graph will not help us find an answer such as 3.2134. For these reasons we
will rarely use graphs to solve a given system of equations. Instead, an algebraic approach
will be used.\pp
</p>
  
<p>
The first algebraic approach is called substitution. We will build the
concepts of substitution through several examples, then end with a five-step
process to solve problems using this method.
</p>
  
<example><statement>
<p>
<nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp />Solve the following system of equations.
</p>
  
<me>
x=5\qquad\qquad y=2x-3
</me>
 
<p>
We already know <m>x</m> must equal 5, so we can substitute <m>x=5</m> into the other equation.
</p>
  
<md><mrow>y = 2 \tmmathbf{(5)} - 3 \amp   \amp  \tmop{Evaluate:} \tmop{~Multiply}
    \tmop{first}</mrow>
 <mrow>y = 10 - 3~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Next~subtract}</mrow>
 <mrow>y = 7~~~~~~~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{We} \tmop{now} \tmop{also} \tmop{have} y</mrow>
 <mrow>(x,y)=(5, 7) \amp   \amp  \tmop{Our} \tmop{solution}</mrow>
 
</md>
 </statement>
</example>
  
<p>
When we know what one variable equals we can plug that value (or expression)
in for the variable in the other equation. It is very important that when we
substitute, the substituted value goes in parentheses. The reason for this is
shown in the next example.
</p>
  
<p>

<nbsp /><br />
</p>
  
<example><statement>
<p>
<nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp />Solve the following system of equations.
</p>
  
<me>
2 x - 3 y = 7\qquad\qquad y = 3 x - 7
</me>
 
<p>
We begin by substituting <m>y=3x-7</m> into the other equation.
</p>
  
<md><mrow>2 x - 3 \tmmathbf{(3 x - 7)} = 7~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Solve~for} x, 
		\tmop{distributing} - 3 \tmop{first}</mrow>
 <mrow>2 x - 9 x + 21 = 7~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Combine} \tmop{like} \tmop{terms} 2 x - 9x</mrow>
 <mrow>- 7 x + 21 = 7~~~~ \amp   \amp </mrow>
 <mrow>\underline{\tmmathbf{- 21 ~~- 21}} \amp   \amp  \tmop{Subtract} 21</mrow>
 <mrow>- 7 x = - 14 \amp   \amp </mrow>
 <mrow>\tmmathbf{\overline{- 7} ~~~~~ \overline{- 7}} \amp   \amp  \tmop{Divide} \tmop{by} - 7</mrow>
 <mrow>x = 2~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{We} \tmop{now} \tmop{have} \tmop{our} x.</mrow>
 <mrow>\amp  \amp  \tmop{~~~Substitute} \tmop{back} \tmop{in} \tmop{equation} \tmop{to} \tmop{find} y</mrow>
 <mrow>y = 3 \tmmathbf{(2)} - 7 \amp   \amp  \tmop{Evaluate:} \tmop{~Multiply} \tmop{first}</mrow>
 <mrow>y = 6 - 7~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Next~subtract}</mrow>
 <mrow>y = - 1~~~~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{We} \tmop{now} \tmop{also} \tmop{have} y</mrow>
 <mrow>(x,y)=(2, - 1) \amp   \amp  \tmop{Our} \tmop{solution}</mrow>
 
</md>
 </statement>
</example>
 
<p>
By using the entire expression <m>3 x - 7</m> to replace <m>y</m> in the other equation
we were able to reduce the system to a single linear equation which we can
easily solve for our first variable. However, the "lone" variable (a variable
with a coefficient of 1) is not always alone on one side of the equation. If
this happens we can isolate the lone variable by solving for it.
</p>
  
<example><statement>
<p>
<nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp />Solve the following system of equations.
</p>
  
<me>
3 x + 2 y = 1\qquad\qquad \tmmathbf{x} - 5 y = 6
</me>
 
<p>
The lone variable is <m>x</m>. Isolate the lone variable by adding <m>5y</m> to both sides.
</p>
  
<md><mrow>x - 5 y = 6~~~~~~~ \amp  \amp </mrow>
 <mrow>\tmmathbf{\underline{+ 5 y ~~+ 5 y}}~~~  \amp   \amp </mrow>
 <mrow>x = 6 + 5 y \amp   \amp  \tmop{Substitute} \tmop{this} \tmop{into} \tmop{the}
  		\tmop{untouched} \tmop{equation}</mrow>
 <mrow>\amp  \amp </mrow>
 <mrow>3 \tmmathbf{(6 + 5 y)} + 2 y = 1 \amp   \amp  \tmop{Solve} \tmop{this}
    \tmop{equation}, \tmop{distributing} 3 \tmop{first}</mrow>
 <mrow>18 + 15 y + 2 y = 1 \amp   \amp  \tmop{Combine} \tmop{like} \tmop{terms} 15 y + 2
    y</mrow>
  
</md>
  
<md><mrow>18 + 17 y = 1~~~~ \amp   \amp </mrow>
 <mrow>\tmmathbf{\underline{- 18 ~~~~~~~~~- 18}} \amp   \amp  \tmop{Subtract} 18 \tmop{from} \tmop{both}
    \tmop{sides}</mrow>
 <mrow>17 y = - 17 \amp   \amp </mrow>
 <mrow>\tmmathbf{\overline{17} ~~~~~~ \overline{17}} \amp   \amp   \tmop{Divide} \tmop{both} \tmop{sides} \tmop{by} 17</mrow>
 <mrow>y = - 1 ~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{We} \tmop{have} \tmop{our} y.</mrow>
 <mrow>\amp  \amp  \tmop{~~~Substitute} \tmop{back} \tmop{in} \tmop{equation} \tmop{to} \tmop{find} x</mrow>
 <mrow>x = 6 + 5 \tmmathbf{(- 1)} \amp   \amp  \tmop{Evaluate:} \tmop{~Multiply} \tmop{first}</mrow>
 <mrow>x = 6 - 5~~~~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Next~subtract}</mrow>
 <mrow>x = 1~~~~~~~~~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{We} \tmop{now} \tmop{also} \tmop{have} x</mrow>
 <mrow>(x,y)=(1, - 1) \amp   \amp  \tmop{Our} \tmop{solution}</mrow>
 
</md>
 </statement>
</example>
  
<p>
The process in the previous example is known as solving by substitution. This process is described and illustrated in the following table which lists the five steps to solving by substitution.\pp
</p>
