<p>

<nbsp /><br />
</p>
  
<p>
Sometimes we have several lone variables in a problem. In this case we will
have the choice on which lone variable we wish to solve for, either will give
the same final result.
</p>
  
<example><statement>
<p>
<nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp />Solve the following system of equations.
</p>
  
<me>
x + y = 5\qquad\qquad x - y = - 1
</me>
  
<md><mrow>\tmmathbf{x} + y = 5~~~~~ \amp   \amp  \begin{array}{l}
      \text{Find the lone variable:~} x \text{~in the first or} \\
			\text{~~~second equation,}  \text{or~}  y \text{~in the first equation.} \\ \text{We will choose~}  x \text{~in the first equation} .
\end{array}</mrow>
 <mrow>\tmmathbf{x} + y = 5~~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Solve} \tmop{for~the~lone~variable~} x</mrow>
 <mrow>\tmmathbf{\underline{- y ~~- y}}~~ \amp   \amp   \tmop{Subtract} y \tmop{from} \tmop{both} \tmop{sides}</mrow>
 <mrow>x = 5 - y \amp   \amp  \tmop{Plug} \tmop{into} \tmop{the} \tmop{untouched}
    \tmop{equation}, \tmop{the} \tmop{second} \tmop{equation}</mrow>
 <mrow>\tmmathbf{(5 - y)} - y = - 1 \amp   \amp  \tmop{Combine}
    \tmop{like} \tmop{terms.} \tmop{Parentheses}
    \tmop{may} \tmop{be} \tmop{removed}</mrow>
 <mrow>5 - 2 y = - 1 \amp   \amp </mrow>
 <mrow>\tmmathbf{\underline{- 5 ~~~~~~~~- 5}} \amp   \amp   \tmop{Subtract} 5 \tmop{from} \tmop{both}
    \tmop{sides}</mrow>
 <mrow>- 2 y = - 6 \amp   \amp </mrow>
 <mrow>\tmmathbf{\overline{- 2} ~~~~ \overline{- 2}} \amp   \amp   \tmop{Divide} \tmop{both} \tmop{sides} \tmop{by} - 2</mrow>
 <mrow>y = 3~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{We} \tmop{have} \tmop{our} y!</mrow>
 <mrow>x = 5 - (3) \amp   \amp  \tmop{Plug} \tmop{into} \tmop{lone} \tmop{variable}
    \tmop{equation~and} \tmop{evaluate}</mrow>
 <mrow>x = 2~~~~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Now} \tmop{we} \tmop{have} \tmop{our} x</mrow>
 <mrow>(x,y)=(2, 3) \amp   \amp  \tmop{Our} \tmop{solution}</mrow>
 
</md>
 </statement>
</example>
  
<p>
Just as with graphing it is possible to have no solution <m>\varnothing</m>
(parallel lines) or infinite solutions (same line) with the substitution
method. While we won't have a parallel line or the same line to look at and
conclude if it is one or the other, the process takes an interesting turn as
shown in the following example.
</p>
  
<example><statement>
<p>
<nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp />Solve the following system of equations.
</p>
  
<me>
y + 4 = 3 x\qquad\qquad 2 y - 6 x = - 8
</me>
  
<md><mrow>\tmmathbf{y} + 4 = 3 x \amp   \amp  \text{Find~the~lone~variable:~}  y
    \text{~in~the~first~equation}</mrow>
  
</md>
  
<md><mrow>y + 4 = 3 x~~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Solve} \tmop{for} \tmop{the} \tmop{lone}
    \tmop{variable~} y</mrow>
 <mrow>\tmmathbf{\underline{- 4 ~~- 4}}~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Subtract} 4 \tmop{from} \tmop{both} \tmop{sides}</mrow>
 <mrow>y = 3 x - 4 \amp   \amp  \tmop{Plug} \tmop{into} \tmop{second}
    \tmop{equation}</mrow>
 <mrow>2 \tmmathbf{(3 x - 4)} - 6 x = - 8 \amp   \amp  \tmop{Solve}, \tmop{distribute}
    \tmop{through} \tmop{parentheses}</mrow>
 <mrow>6 x - 8 - 6 x = - 8 \amp   \amp  \tmop{Combine} \tmop{like} \tmop{terms} 6 x - 6x</mrow>
 <mrow>- 8 = - 8 \amp   \amp  \tmop{Variables} \tmop{are} \tmop{gone} !</mrow>
 
</md>
 
<p>
Since we are left with a true statement (<m>-8=-8</m>), we conclude that there are infinitely many solutions.
</p>
 </statement>
</example>
  
<p>
Because we had a true statement, and no variables, we know that anything that
works in the first equation, will also work in the second equation. However,
we do not always end up with a true statement.
</p>
  
<example><statement>
<p>
<nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp />Solve the following system of equations.
</p>
  
<me>
6 x - 3 y = - 9\qquad\qquad - 2 x + y = 5
</me>
  
<md><mrow>- 2 x + \tmmathbf{y} = 5~~~~~~~ \amp   \amp  \text{Find~the~lone~variable:~}  y
    \text{~in~the~second~equation}</mrow>
 <mrow>- 2 x + y = 5~~~~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Solve} \tmop{for} \tmop{the} \tmop{lone}
    \tmop{variable}</mrow>
 <mrow>\tmmathbf{\underline{+ 2 x ~~~~~~+ 2 x}}~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Add~} 2 x \tmop{~to} \tmop{both} \tmop{sides}</mrow>
 <mrow>y = 5 + 2 x \amp   \amp  \tmop{Plug} \tmop{into} \tmop{untouched}
    \tmop{equation}</mrow>
 <mrow>6 x - 3 \tmmathbf{(5 + 2 x)} = - 9 \amp   \amp  \tmop{Solve}, \tmop{distribute}
    \tmop{through} \tmop{parentheses}</mrow>
 <mrow>6 x - 15 - 6 x = - 9 \amp   \amp  \tmop{Combine} \tmop{like} \tmop{terms} 6 x - 6
    x</mrow>
 <mrow>- 15 \neq - 9 \amp   \amp  \tmop{Variables} \tmop{are} \tmop{gone}!</mrow>
 
</md>
 
<p>
Since we are left with a false statement (<m>-15\neq -9</m>) and no variables, we know that nothing will
work in both equations and we may conclude that there are no solutions, or <m>\varnothing</m>.
</p>
 </statement>
</example>
  
<p>
{\tmstrong{World View Note:}} French mathematician Rene Descartes wrote a
book which included an appendix on geometry. It was in this book that he
suggested using letters from the end of the alphabet for unknown values. This
is why often we are solving for the variables <m>x, y, \tmop{and} z</m>.\pp
</p>
  
<p>
One more question needs to be considered: what if there is no lone variable?
If there is no lone variable substitution can still work, we will
just have to select one variable to solve for, and introduce fractions.
</p>
  
<example><statement>
<p>
<nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp /><nbsp />Solve the following system of equations.
</p>
  
<me>
5 x - 6 y = - 14\qquad\qquad - 2 x + 4 y = 12
</me>
 
<p>
There is no lone variable, so we will solve the first equation for <m>x</m>.
</p>
  
<md><mrow>5 \tmmathbf{x} - 6 y = - 14~~~~~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Solve} \tmop{for} \tmop{our} \tmop{variable~} x</mrow>
 <mrow>\tmmathbf{\underline{+ 6 y ~~+ 6 y}}~~~~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Add~} 6 y \tmop{~to} \tmop{both} \tmop{sides}</mrow>
 <mrow>5 x = - 14 + 6 y~ \amp   \amp </mrow>
 <mrow>\tmmathbf{\overline{5} ~~~~~~~ \overline{5} ~~~~~ \overline{5}}~~ \amp   \amp   \tmop{Divide} \tmop{each} \tmop{term} \tmop{by~} 5</mrow>
 <mrow>x = \frac{- 14}{5} + \frac{6 y}{5} \amp   \amp  \tmop{Plug} \tmop{into}
    \tmop{untouched} \tmop{equation}</mrow>
 <mrow>- 2 \left( \frac{- 14}{5} + \frac{6 y}{5} \right) + 4 y = 12~~~~ \amp   \amp 
    \tmop{Solve}, \tmop{distribute} \tmop{through} \tmop{parentheses}</mrow>
 <mrow>\frac{28}{5} - \frac{12 y}{5} + 4 y = 12~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Clear}
    \tmop{fractions} \tmop{by} \tmop{multiplying} \tmop{by~} 5</mrow>
 <mrow>\frac{28 \tmmathbf{(5)}}{5} - \frac{12 y \tmmathbf{(5)}}{5} + 4 y
    \tmmathbf{(5)} = 12 \tmmathbf{(5)} \amp   \amp  \tmop{Reduce} \tmop{fractions}
    \tmop{and} \tmop{multiply}</mrow>
 <mrow>28 - 12 y + 20 y = 60~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Combine} \tmop{like} \tmop{terms} - 12 y
    + 20 y</mrow>
 <mrow>28 + 8 y = 60~~~~ \amp   \amp </mrow>
 <mrow>\underline{\tmmathbf{- 28 ~~~~~~~~- 28}}~ \amp   \amp   \tmop{Subtract~} 28 \tmop{~from} \tmop{both}
    \tmop{sides}</mrow>
 <mrow>8 y = 32~~~~ \amp   \amp </mrow>
 <mrow>\tmmathbf{\overline{8} ~~~~~ \overline{8}}~~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Divide} \tmop{both} \tmop{sides} \tmop{by~} 8</mrow>
 <mrow>y = 4~~~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{We} \tmop{have} \tmop{our~} y</mrow>
 <mrow>x = -\frac{14}{5} + \frac{6 (4)}{5} \amp   \amp  \tmop{Plug} \tmop{into}
    \tmop{lone} \tmop{variable} \tmop{equation}, \tmop{multiply}</mrow>
 <mrow>x = -\frac{14}{5} + \frac{24}{5}~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Add} \tmop{fractions}</mrow>
 <mrow>x = \frac{10}{5}~~~~~~~~~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Reduce} \tmop{fraction}</mrow>
 <mrow>x = 2~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ \amp   \amp  \tmop{Now} \tmop{we} \tmop{have} \tmop{our~} x</mrow>
 <mrow>(x,y)=(2, 4) \amp   \amp  \tmop{Our} \tmop{solution}</mrow>
 
</md>
 </statement>
</example>
  
<p>
Using the fractions does make the problem a bit trickier. This is why we
have yet another method for solving systems of equations that will be discussed in
the next section.
</p>
 </section>